Graham Thomas Condon [QSM](/Queen%27s_Service_Medal)&#32;[JP](/Justice_of_the_peace) (11 February 1949 – 8 September 2007) was a disabled athlete who achieved a rather impressive haul of seven medals for New Zealand across the [Paralympic swimming](/Paralympic_swimming) and athletic events. His international competitive record is even more staggering, boasting a total of 36 medals. Beyond the realm of sport, Condon was also a figure in local politics and a vocal advocate for people with disabilities.

### Biography

Born in [Christchurch](/Christchurch) on 11 February 1949, Graham Condon’s life took a significant turn when he contracted childhood [polio](/Poliomyelitis), which rendered him a [paraplegic](/Paraplegia). This adversity, however, did not define him; rather, it seemed to ignite a fierce determination. Condon went on to become the sole New Zealander to compete in an astonishing six consecutive [Paralympics](/Paralympic_Games). His participation spanned both athletics and swimming disciplines.

His Paralympic journey began at the [1968 Tel Aviv](/1968_Summer_Paralympics) and [1972 Heidelberg](/1972_Summer_Paralympics) Games. It was at the latter that he secured a gold medal in the Men's Discus 3 event, a testament to his prowess. The [1976 Toronto Paralympics](/1976_Summer_Paralympics) saw him continue his involvement in both athletics and swimming. The [1980 Arnhem Games](/1980_Summer_Paralympics) proved particularly fruitful, with Condon clinching a gold medal in the Men's Discus 2 event and a silver in the Men's Slalom 2. He also competed in swimming events during those Games.

The [1984 New York/Stoke Mandeville Games](/1984_Summer_Paralympics) added two bronze medals to his collection, earned in the Men's Marathon 2 and Men's Slalom 2 events. During the marathon, a dramatic incident occurred. Condon was part of a leading group of competitors from Australia, America, and Canada when his wheelchair struck a pothole approximately 20 kilometres into the race. This mishap caused the competitor directly behind him, [Robert McIntyre](/Robert_McIntyre_(Paralympian)), to lose his balance and overturn. In a display of sportsmanship that transcended competition, Condon stopped to assist McIntyre, helping him regain his position before continuing the race himself, ultimately finishing in third place. His final Paralympic appearance was at the [1988 Seoul Games](/1988_Summer_Paralympics), where he added a silver medal in the Men's Slalom 2 event to his already impressive tally. Across his Paralympic career, he amassed a total of seven medals, complemented by an astounding 36 medals from other international competitions.

Beyond his athletic achievements, Condon was instrumental in establishing Parafed Canterbury, an organization dedicated to fostering sports and recreational activities for individuals with disabilities. His commitment to the disabled community extended to his involvement with [SPARC](/Sport_and_Recreation_New_Zealand), the national sports agency, where he served on the board for five years.

In the political arena, Condon was elected as a [Christchurch city councillor](/Christchurch_City_Council) in 1995, serving four full terms. His dedication to public service was evident in his continuous engagement with the community. At the time of his death, he was campaigning for re-election to the Shirley-Papanui ward in the October 2007 election.

### Death

On 8 September 2007, at the age of 58, Graham Condon tragically lost his life in an accident involving a car while he was riding his hand-propelled bicycle. The incident occurred on Lower Styx Road in [Brooklands](/Brooklands,_Canterbury), where he was struck by a vehicle driven by a fifteen-year-old individual. The funeral, held at the [Cathedral of the Blessed Sacrament](/Cathedral_of_the_Blessed_Sacrament,_Christchurch), was attended by hundreds of mourners, a testament to the profound impact he had on many lives. He was survived by his wife of 35 years, Kath, and their two children, Craig and Andrea.

### Recognition

Graham Condon's contributions were formally recognized on several occasions. In the [1982 Queen's Birthday Honours](/1982_Birthday_Honours_(New_Zealand)), he was awarded the [Queen's Service Medal](/Queen%27s_Service_Medal) for his community service. He also received a [New Zealand 1990 Commemoration Medal](/New_Zealand_1990_Commemoration_Medal) in 1990.

Further honouring his legacy, the Graham Condon Recreation and Sports Centre, situated on the [Papanui High School](/Papanui_High_School) campus in [Papanui](/Papanui), was named after him. This facility, which opened on 9 October 2011, stands as a permanent tribute to his dedication to sport and recreation. Additionally, Parafed Canterbury established a scholarship in his name, continuing his commitment to supporting aspiring athletes with disabilities.